<br />
wow.  neither of us have the combined sales figures for the netbook industry, so it&#39;s not like we can talk with any authority about how many units shipped with sdd or hdd.  <a href=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comparison_of_netbooks target=x>this</a> shows 28 out of 82 netbooks shipping with at least an sdd option, so that&#39;s a third.  Anecdotally I know from shopping for a netbook two years ago that most I models came in two versions, one with the hdd and one with the sdd.  like i said, i haven&#39;t paid much attention to netbooks since 2009, other than to see that netbook sales have been dropping, but yes apparently at this point in time the ssd netbook has fallen by the wayside.  i can only assume that the average consumer saw two similar computer at about the same price, one with many more GB of storage listed on the info card, and they went with the larger number without bothering to ask what was the reason behind the difference.<br />
<br />
<blockquote><i>And the ones that did ship with SSDs either had hilariously small hard drives or were ridiculously expensive (like Sony&#39;s netbook).</i></blockquote><br />
when you throw up a standard saying ppl need 64 gb of storage, then yes, every ssd in every type of device will be hilariously small or ridiculously expensive. and that&#39;s why i said pair an ssd with an hdd (external for a laptop, internal for a desktop) for the best of both worlds.  put your OS and programs on the sdd for fast loading and access times.  and store your personal files (music, video, etc.) on the larger hdd.  <br><BR><font size=1>18:54 02-24-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Jedi Genius </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/vs/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Jedi Genius '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">Half of all netbooks did not ship with SSDs, that&#39;s a blatant lie. If you do a search of all existing netbooks in stock anywhere, you&#39;ll see the standard is 160-250GB platter drives (that&#39;s the ones with spinning disks/moving parts, Neal). And the ones that did ship with SSDs either had hilariously small hard drives or were ridiculously expensive (like Sony&#39;s netbook). <br />
<br />
They aren&#39;t in most laptops right now because of cost, plain and simple. You go to Best Buy and look at the laptops - the majority of them are in the $400-800 price range in various sizes... they&#39;ve replaced desktops in a lot of cases when it comes to what the typical consumer will buy. For that amount of money, sure, you could throw in a super low capacity SSD... but since this is someone&#39;s primary computer, they want the storage space for their photos, videos, and music (among other things), and a 64GB SSD simply wouldn&#39;t cut it. <br />
<br />
It works in the Macbook Air because that&#39;s typically someone&#39;s second computer. Very rarely does anyone purchase an ultraportable as their primary computer. <br />
<br />
By the way, advantages of SSDs over HDDs (platter drives):<br />
- Faster read/write<br />
- No moving parts (less prone to break)<br />
- Less heat generation (but largely this matters little, since it&#39;s usually other components that heat up your laptop a lot more than your hard drive ever will)<br />
<br />
The disadvantage is, and always has been, cost. And dollars drive everything. It&#39;s the same reason super high resolution monitors with perfect color reproduction aren&#39;t in every laptop - they cost a ton and people buying $400-700 laptops don&#39;t care about that stuff. <br><BR><font size=1>17:46 02-24-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=17">Dredlox™</a></B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/vs/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=<a href="http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=17">Dredlox™</a>'>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">what&#39;s a platter drive, walt?  I know one reason ssds are popular in laptops is energy use.  Nothing spinning = less power usage = longer battery life <br><BR><font size=1>08:41 02-24-2011</font><BR><BR><img src=http://www.takepart.com/sites/default/files/imagecache/80x80/logos/220354-defenders_of_wildlife_o.jpg></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Walter Crunkite </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/vs/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Walter Crunkite '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont"><blockquote><i>You have to go to the $1k MacBook Air before you find a laptop with a standard SSD (64GB of storage!), virtually everything cheaper than that still has a standard platter drive.</i></blockquote><br />
i haven&#39;t kept up with things, but a year or two ago (before they died), like half of all netbooks shipped with a ssd, while the other half shipped with platter drives (and both sold for around $300).<br />
<br />
I honestly don&#39;t see why ssds are more popular in laptops.  they let you subject your machine to all sorts of punishment without having to worry that even the littlest bump may have bent your hd platters or read heads and ruined your computer.  yeah they can&#39;t compare to platter drives in terms of storage, but that&#39;s what external drives are made for <br><BR><font size=1>22:53 02-23-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=17">Dredlox™</a></B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/vs/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=<a href="http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=17">Dredlox™</a>'>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">I think I give hard drives 10 years. <br><BR><font size=1>19:43 02-23-2011</font><BR><BR><img src=http://www.takepart.com/sites/default/files/imagecache/80x80/logos/220354-defenders_of_wildlife_o.jpg></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=17">Dredlox™</a></B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/vs/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=<a href="http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=17">Dredlox™</a>'>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">I&#39;m just teasing you Brandon.  You are extremely knowledgeable about tech <br><BR><font size=1>19:42 02-23-2011</font><BR><BR><img src=http://www.takepart.com/sites/default/files/imagecache/80x80/logos/220354-defenders_of_wildlife_o.jpg></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#C3E3FF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B>Jedi Genius </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/vs/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Jedi Genius '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">At the time you asked, I provided performance charts (You know, facts) to back my statement.<br />
<br />
I never said they wouldn&#39;t be faster in the future. But at the same time, your question in the title is "are hard drives done for?" The answer remains: Hell no. Platter drives (typical hard drives) will remain for quite a while since they offer by far the best storage for your dollar. SSDs are still hard drives, and aren&#39;t very economical to use in any standard build if you need more than 64GB of space. <br />
<br />
Consumers don&#39;t value speed over total storage still, the claim you make in your first post, or else every base level laptop would come with a 32GB SSD instead of a 160GB-500GB platter hard drive. You have to go to the $1k MacBook Air before you find a laptop with a standard SSD (64GB of storage!), virtually everything cheaper than that still has a standard platter drive.<br />
<br />
In the distant future, will the switch be made? But people will still have external drives that are platter, servers will be run on platter drives, and the cloud (servers) will also run on them (because they will almost always outpace a network connection anyway). <br />
<br />
But it isn&#39;t about performance (which is why they remain in only high end laptops), it&#39;s about storage and price.  <br><BR><font size=1>17:55 02-23-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Patrick M. S </B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/vs/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=Patrick M. S '>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">lol, yeah what an IDIOT <br><BR><font size=1>10:28 02-23-2011</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' valign='top' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><img src='/global/images/premium_icon.gif' border='0' hspace='1' vspace='1'></td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#C3E3FF><font class="bfont"><B><a href="http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=17">Dredlox™</a></B></font><br><font class="afont"> <A HREF='/vs/resources/buzz.php?ignorename=<a href="http://www.decktech.net/magic/main/mpage.php?member=17">Dredlox™</a>'>Ignore</A></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#C3E3FF' ><font class="bfont">He can read it perfectly. For exactly 6 months!<br />
